&gt;&gt; PINKER: Thank you so much. It's a real

00:01:21.899 --> 00:01:27.190
pleasure and honor to be here. This old wood
cut of the story of the blind man and the

00:01:27.190 --> 00:01:32.829
elephant is a reminder that any complex subject
can be studied in many ways. And that is certainly

00:01:32.829 --> 00:01:40.460
true for a subject as complex as human nature.
Anthropology can study universal patterns

00:01:40.460 --> 00:01:44.969
of the belief and behavior across the world's
societies as well as the ways in which they

00:01:44.969 --> 00:01:50.630
defer. Biology can document how the process
of evolution selected the genes that helped

00:01:50.630 --> 00:01:57.950
to wire the brain. Psychology, my own field,
can get people to disclose their foibles in

00:01:57.950 --> 00:02:04.009
laboratory studies, and even fiction can illuminate
human nature by showing the universal themes

00:02:04.009 --> 00:02:09.500
and plots that obsess people in their myths
and stories. This afternoon, I'm going to

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:14.110
give you the view from language: what kind
of insight we can gain into thought, emotion

00:02:14.110 --> 00:02:19.400
and social relations from words and how we
use them. I'll talk about grammar as a window

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:27.320
into thought, swearing as a window into emotion,
and innuendo as a window into social relationships.

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:32.480
And in each case, I'll start with a puzzle
in language show how it reveals a much deeper

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:38.080
feature of the human mind using specific examples
from English, the language of which all of

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:43.760
us are familiar. But examples that have close
counterparts in many languages and that follow

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:49.080
an overall logic that can be found in all
languages. So let's begin with language as

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:53.830
a window into thought. And the puzzle I will
start off with comes from a delightful book

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:58.830
by Richard Lederer called "Crazy English"
which has the following passage: "You have

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:03.920
to marvel at the unique lunacy of a language
where a house can burn up as it burns down,

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:09.120
and in which you fill in a form by filling
it out. Why is it called 'after dark' when

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:14.120
it is really after light? Things that we claim
are underwater and underground are surrounded

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:20.080
by, not under the water and ground." So the
first puzzle is why languages talk about the

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:24.860
physical world in such crazy ways. And the
answer I'm going to suggest is that there

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:30.030
is a theory of physics embedded in our language:
A concept of space in our prepositions, a

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:33.326
concept of matter in our nouns, a concept
of space in our propositions, a concept of

00:03:33.326 --> 00:03:36.120
a matter in our nouns, a concept of time in
our tenses, and a concept of causality in

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:41.640
our verbs. That understanding the intuitive
physics in language helps to explain not just

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:46.970
the quirks of language itself but the mental
models that humans use to make sense of their

00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:53.740
lives. So, let's start off with space. How
do we locate an object relative to a place,

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:59.900
a reference location or coordinate frame?
Well, you can imagine an ideal hypothetical

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:06.560
system of prepositions where every proposition
was composed of six syllables: one each for

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:11.670
distance in the up-down, left-right and front-back
direction, and then one each for the angle

00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:19.590
of pitch, roll and yaw. Needless to say, no
language uses this system. Instead, location

00:04:19.590 --> 00:04:25.120
is digitized. Languages make distinctions
like near versus far, on versus off, in versus

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:29.900
out, on versus under. Which is why Groucho
could say, "If I could held you any closer,

00:04:29.900 --> 00:04:36.520
I'd be on the other side of you." Also scale
is relative. You can use the same spatial

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:42.469
term across to refer to an ant walking across
a hand or a bus driving across the country.

00:04:42.469 --> 00:04:47.610
And the interpretation of the word "there"
will defer in a sentence like put it there,

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:53.860
depending on whether the person uttering it
is a crane operator or a brain surgeon. Also

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:59.810
shape is schematic. In reality, all objects
are 3-dimentional arrangements of matter.

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:05.020
But language idealizes them as essentially
1-deminsional, 2-dimensional, or 3-dimensional.

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:11.629
So we've got a line which courses a 1-dimentional,
but also a road which is conceived up as 1-dimentional

00:05:11.629 --> 00:05:17.930
with a little width flashing it out, and a
beam which is also conceived as 1-dimentional

00:05:17.930 --> 00:05:23.130
but with a finite thickness flashing it out.
In contrast, we've got a surface which is

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:29.020
2-dimentional or a slab also construed as
2-dimentional with some finite thickness.

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:34.620
This idealized geometry governs are used of
prepositions. So, for example the preposition

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:39.810
"along" requires an essentially 1-dimentional
object. You can say the ant walked along the

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:44.650
line or along the road or along the beam,
but not the ant walked along the plate or

00:05:44.650 --> 00:05:50.900
along the ball which sounds a little anomalous.
It governs the way we apply nouns to shape.

00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:56.080
So we don't refer to a wire as a cylinder
as a long, skinny cylinder, nor a CD is a

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:00.990
cylinder, a short fat one even though geometrically
speaking that's what they are. But because

00:06:00.990 --> 00:06:06.539
we ignore certain dimensions as insubstantial
and idealize the shape as one of the remaining

00:06:06.539 --> 00:06:11.969
dimensions. And I think it goes into our overall
sense of shape, what we conceive of as similar

00:06:11.969 --> 00:06:17.349
to what else, as when a child says, "I don't
want a little crayon box. I want the box that

00:06:17.349 --> 00:06:23.099
looks like audience." That is not the eight
box of eight crayon box of Crayola, but the

00:06:23.099 --> 00:06:28.050
sixty-four Crayon box where the crayons are
arranged in pitched rows like the balcony

00:06:28.050 --> 00:06:34.879
of an auditorium. A fourth quirk is that the
boundaries of object are treated like objects

00:06:34.879 --> 00:06:38.849
themselves. And this is something you may
have heard of, heard from Ray Jackendoff,

00:06:38.849 --> 00:06:43.849
my colleague who I understood stands--spoke
here recently. We have words like "edge" which

00:06:43.849 --> 00:06:48.169
refer to the 1-D boundary of a 2-D surface.
And so, we could say the ant walked along

00:06:48.169 --> 00:06:53.370
the edge of the plate, even if we can't see
the ant walked along the plate. Or, and word

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:58.419
like "end" which is the boundary either of
a 1-D ribbon or a 2-D beam, as long it's essentially

00:06:58.419 --> 00:07:03.789
1-D. And you could even cut the end off a
ribbon, which geometrically speaking ought

00:07:03.789 --> 00:07:08.870
to be impossible but we conceive of the end
as if it was an object itself. That explains

00:07:08.870 --> 00:07:12.620
the mystery of why we say, "underwater" and
"underground" when the thing is surrounded

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:18.180
by water or ground. It's because the word
"water" or "ground" can refer to the 2-D surface

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:24.719
of the 3-D volume, not just the 3-D volume
itself, and you can be under that surface.

00:07:24.719 --> 00:07:28.999
So why is the language of space so crazy?
Well, I think the main reason is that preposition

00:07:28.999 --> 00:07:34.550
divide up space into regions with different
causal consequences. And the clearest illustration

00:07:34.550 --> 00:07:39.979
of that comes from a story that I clipped
out at the Boston Globe a few years ago: Woman

00:07:39.979 --> 00:07:44.660
rescued from frozen pond dies. A woman who
fell through thin ice Sunday and was under

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:49.900
water for 90 minutes died yesterday. The Lincoln
Fire Department said a miscommunication between

00:07:49.900 --> 00:07:55.389
the caller who reported the accident and the
dispatcher significantly delayed her rescue.

00:07:55.389 --> 00:08:00.400
The rescue workers believed that a woman had
fallen on the ice, not through it, and that

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:04.319
left the rescuers combing the woods to find
the scene of the accident. So that digital

00:08:04.319 --> 00:08:09.029
distinction between "on" and "through" in
this case was literally a matter of life and

00:08:09.029 --> 00:08:14.810
death even though it involved just a couple
of feet in analog space. Let me turn to substance

00:08:14.810 --> 00:08:22.969
in language. Language distinguishes stuff
from things. Indeed, language taxonomises

00:08:22.969 --> 00:08:29.749
matter into four categories. There are countable
things as an apple; masses as in much apple

00:08:29.749 --> 00:08:35.979
sauce; plurals as in many apples; and collections
as in a dozen apples. These aren't so much

00:08:35.979 --> 00:08:44.040
different kinds of matter as different frames
or attitudes in looking at matter which is

00:08:44.040 --> 00:08:49.540
why we can look at the same mass of little
rocks and think of it either as pebbles, a

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:55.580
collection of individuals or as gravel, an
amorphous stuff, and why we have the cliche

00:08:55.580 --> 00:09:01.730
about the person who can't see the forest
for the trees. In Crazy English, Lederer asks,

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:08.100
"Why does a man with hair on his head have
more hair than a man with hairs on his head?"

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:12.820
Why is the language of substance so crazy?
Well, words for matter allow people to agree

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:20.070
on how to package and quantify the continuous
material world. In an obvious context in which

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:25.790
we see that is at the supermarket where chunks
of matter have to be transacted and they can

00:09:25.790 --> 00:09:30.460
be priced per item, which is what a count
noun does; by weight, which is what a mass

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:35.290
noun does; or by the dozen, which is what
a collective noun does. And in fact, that

00:09:35.290 --> 00:09:41.040
same mindset that we apply to packaging matter
in the physical world, we also apply to abstract

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:45.580
concepts. So just as we have the distinction
between pebbles and gravel, we have a distinction

00:09:45.580 --> 00:09:52.100
between many opinions as if they were discrete
object and much advice as if it was an amorphous

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:57.890
mass. We do the same thing to happenings in
time. We package the flow of experience in

00:09:57.890 --> 00:10:03.090
the same way that we package the continuum
of matter. For example, let's say I would

00:10:03.090 --> 00:10:08.630
ask you, how many events took place in the
morning of 9/11 in New York City? One answer

00:10:08.630 --> 00:10:15.030
is there was one event, because a single plan
was executed. You can demarcate events by

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:19.970
the realization of a plan. Another answer
is two, because two buildings were destroyed.

00:10:19.970 --> 00:10:26.340
You can demarcate time by salient physical
events. This might seem like the height of

00:10:26.340 --> 00:10:33.290
pointless semantic nitpicking or hairsplitting,
but in fact it is a question with consequences

00:10:33.290 --> 00:10:37.570
because the lease holder for the World Trade
Center had an insurance policy that entitled

00:10:37.570 --> 00:10:43.970
them to 3.5 billion dollars per destructive
event. If 9/11 comprised one event, he stood

00:10:43.970 --> 00:10:48.600
to gain three and half billion. If it comprised
two events, he stood to gain seven billion.

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:53.510
And in a number of court cases tied up for
many years, the lawyers debated this issue

00:10:53.510 --> 00:10:59.150
in semantics. So if anyone says, "How much
is a semantic distinction worth?" The answer

00:10:59.150 --> 00:11:08.320
is $3.5 billion. Well, this brings me to the
language of time. And this illustration reminds

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:13.640
us the time in many ways is conceived like
space, and happenings are conceived like matter

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:18.170
as if there's a kind of "time-stuff" that
could be chopped into the equivalent of objects,

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:23.600
except we call them events. We see this in
the many spatial metaphors for time like "the

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:28.990
deadline is coming," or "we're approaching
the deadline." We see it in kind of errors

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:33.660
that children make like, "Can I have any reading
behind the dinner?" That is, after the dinner

00:11:33.660 --> 00:11:39.490
as if events were stretched out in front of
us. And we see it in the semantics of verb

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:46.170
tense. Now, verb tense, in many ways follows
a semantics that is parallel to the semantics

00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:52.120
of space and matter in the case of prepositions
and nouns. First, time is digitized, and second

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:57.610
time is relative. That is, no language has
tenses for precise intervals of time like

00:11:57.610 --> 00:12:06.670
an hour, nor for locations in time like November
7, 2007. Instead, location in time is trichotomized

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:12.870
in English into three regions to find relative
to the moment of speaking. An event can be

00:12:12.870 --> 00:12:20.150
located in the specious present, an interval
of about three seconds in which we don't make

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:27.570
temporal distinctions. It's the basic unit
of nouns. This is the--specious present is

00:12:27.570 --> 00:12:34.690
a term from William James, and it refers to
an interval of time that embraces a deliberate

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:39.560
action like a handshake, a quick decision
like how long you alight on a channel while

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:44.570
channel surfing and decide whether to click
again, to the decay of unrehearsed short-term

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:50.550
memory to a line of poetry, and to a musical
motif like the opening notes of Beethoven's

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:56.770
Fifth which we don't perceive as just one
note, one note, one note but rather as a coherent

00:12:56.770 --> 00:13:04.840
motif. Then there's the past stretching backwards
indefinitely. So, every event from four seconds

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:12.500
ago back to the big bang is treated as identical
by the English language, which is why Groucho

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:20.860
could say, "I've had a wonderful evening,
but this wasn't it."

00:13:20.860 --> 00:13:26.020
And then, there's the future until eternity,
that is, everything from four seconds from

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:33.290
now until the heat death of the universe all
lumped together. There are not only locations

00:13:33.290 --> 00:13:38.240
in time, what I just referred to, but shapes
in time what linguist call "aspect," that

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:46.010
is, how a happening begins, unfolds, and ends.
Shape in time, like shape in space is treated

00:13:46.010 --> 00:13:53.860
schematically. We conceive of some happenings
as amorphously spread out in time without

00:13:53.860 --> 00:14:00.310
any crisp beginning or end, such as, the verb,
"to shake." We conceive of other events as

00:14:00.310 --> 00:14:05.760
momentaneous or a punctate, such as to swat
a fly. And then, still other events like to

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:12.090
cross the street have no crisp beginning,
but are terminated until some goal has been

00:14:12.090 --> 00:14:18.560
achieved. In this case, you get to the other
side. Now the stretches of time that are defined

00:14:18.560 --> 00:14:23.730
by verbs can also be mentally packaged. In
the same way, that we can take a noun "beer"

00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:29.720
which just refers to the stuff generically
and then package it in a unit by use of the

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:35.300
word "one" as in one beer, turned a mass noun
into a count noun. You can take an amorphous

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:42.390
stretch of time like "shake it" and with the
use of particle like "out" turn it into an

00:14:42.390 --> 00:14:49.310
accomplishment that ends at a defined boundary
as in "shake it up," that is, shake it until

00:14:49.310 --> 00:14:56.570
up to completion. Likewise, we can take "wring
it" which is indefinite in terms of when it

00:14:56.570 --> 00:15:01.570
ends, and give an endpoint with the particle
"out" and say, "wring it out," that is, until

00:15:01.570 --> 00:15:07.950
it's dry. And that is why, a house can burn
up as it burns down, and you can fill in a

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:14.730
form by filling it out. Finally, the boundary
of an event can be treated like an event itself,

00:15:14.730 --> 00:15:19.300
just as with space. Just as I can cut off
the end of a ribbon which is geometrically

00:15:19.300 --> 00:15:23.510
impossible, I can start the end of my talk
which is temporally impossible if you think

00:15:23.510 --> 00:15:30.260
of end as simply the instant of termination.
Why is it called "after dark" when it is really

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:37.790
after light? Well, dark is--refers not just
to the interval of darkness but to the boundary

00:15:37.790 --> 00:15:42.760
of the interval of darkness, and it's exactly
isomorphic to why in the language of space

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:48.400
we can say "underwater" when the thing is
surrounded by water. Why is the language of

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:54.310
time so crazy? Well, we identify locations
in time coarsely, because stretches of time

00:15:54.310 --> 00:15:59.810
relative to the moment of speaking have different
consequences for knowledge and action. And

00:15:59.810 --> 00:16:05.440
a fancy-shmancy way of putting it would be
that there's a bit of metaphysics and epistemology

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:12.120
that's packed into our tense system. It's
not purely a chronological concept. In particular,

00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:17.610
that present tense corresponds to our own
consciousness, to what you can experience

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:25.360
as you're alive and awake and aware, and are
registering your own consciousness. The past

00:16:25.360 --> 00:16:30.490
is not just an interval in time, but that
which is thought to be knowable and factual

00:16:30.490 --> 00:16:37.530
and unchangeable. As in a report of the Scott
Peterson murder case as it was unfolding,

00:16:37.530 --> 00:16:42.210
where investigators noted that Peterson used
the past tense when referring to his wife

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:47.910
and unborn son before their bodies were found,
abruptly correcting himself. His use of the

00:16:47.910 --> 00:16:54.780
past tense betrayed his knowledge of what
he knew had taken place while he was testifying.

00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:58.850
The future conversely we conceive of is not
just any old stretch of time but that which

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:03.670
is unknowable, hypothetical, and willable.
As when Winston Churchill said, "We shall

00:17:03.670 --> 00:17:07.360
fight on the beaches. We shall fight on the
landing grounds. We shall fight in the fields

00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:12.520
and in the streets. We shall fight in the
hills. We shall never surrender." It's deliberately

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:17.389
ambiguous whether he was simply making a prediction
as to what would happen on a future date,

00:17:17.389 --> 00:17:25.949
or whether he was making a declaration of
resolve and will. Those two can't be distinguished,

00:17:25.949 --> 00:17:33.440
and the future tense in English and many other
languages systematically conflates them. And

00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:37.050
finally, we turn to causality of language
where the model of causality in our verbs

00:17:37.050 --> 00:17:44.169
can be summarized in this diagram, that is,
an actor directly impinges on an entity, making

00:17:44.169 --> 00:17:51.750
it move or change. The psychologist, Phillip
Wolff, has done a simple experiment to show

00:17:51.750 --> 00:17:57.750
how this works. He had computer animations.
In one case, Sarah grabbed the doorknob and

00:17:57.750 --> 00:18:02.490
physically swung the door open; in the other
case, she opened the window and a breeze blew

00:18:02.490 --> 00:18:07.710
the door open. If you ask people, "Did Sarah
cause the door to open?" In both cases, people

00:18:07.710 --> 00:18:13.960
say yes. If you then express causality inside
the verb by saying, "Did Sarah open the door?"

00:18:13.960 --> 00:18:19.169
Then in the case where she manhandled the
door, they say yes. In the case where it was

00:18:19.169 --> 00:18:26.429
more circuitous, they say no. Why is the language
of causality so crazy? Well, directly caused

00:18:26.429 --> 00:18:31.080
events are the ones that are most likely to
be foreseeable and intended; hence, those

00:18:31.080 --> 00:18:37.220
for which we can hold people responsible.
And a nice illustration of that comes from

00:18:37.220 --> 00:18:43.429
an episode in American History in 1881, which
shows that when the directness of causation

00:18:43.429 --> 00:18:49.750
is fuzzy, so is our sense of moral and legal
responsibility. President James Garfield was

00:18:49.750 --> 00:18:57.090
waiting for a train in a Baltimore Station,
and Charles Guiteau stalking him, fired two

00:18:57.090 --> 00:19:03.970
shots into him. Now, the bullets missed his
major organs and arteries, and his wound needn't

00:19:03.970 --> 00:19:09.919
have been fatal even in Garfield's time. However,
he was subjected to the harebrained medical

00:19:09.919 --> 00:19:15.460
practices of the day, which included probing
