you are signaling exactly what emotion you're

00:39:51.940 --> 00:39:57.770
feeling. And so it belongs together with other
response-cries in the language like aha, mmm,

00:39:57.770 --> 00:40:05.260
ouch, whoops, wow, yes, and yuck. And therefore
it has that communicative function. So to

00:40:05.260 --> 00:40:10.230
sum-up language as a window into emotion,
humans are prone to strong negative emotions.

00:40:10.230 --> 00:40:17.289
So language tells us awe of the supernatural,
disgust at bodily effluvia, dread of disease,

00:40:17.289 --> 00:40:23.829
hatred of disfavored people and groups, revulsion
at depraved sexual acts. Nonetheless, people

00:40:23.829 --> 00:40:28.809
sometimes want to impose these thoughts on
others to gain their attention, to intimidate

00:40:28.809 --> 00:40:34.710
or humiliate them, to remind them of the awfulness
of the objects and activities, or to advertise

00:40:34.710 --> 00:40:40.740
that one has the normal reactions to misfortunes.
Okay. Part three, language as a window into

00:40:40.740 --> 00:40:47.180
social relations. Again, I'll begin with the
puzzle of language, this one comes from the

00:40:47.180 --> 00:40:52.500
film Fargo, from an early scene in which a
kidnaper has a hostage in the backseat of

00:40:52.500 --> 00:40:57.779
his car, is pulled over by a police officer
because he's missing his plates. He's asked

00:40:57.779 --> 00:41:04.150
to show his driver's license, he hands over
his wallet with the driver's license visible

00:41:04.150 --> 00:41:09.230
and a $50 bill extending ever so slightly
and he says to the officer, "I was thinking

00:41:09.230 --> 00:41:13.740
that maybe the best thing would be to take
care of it here in Brainerd." Which of course

00:41:13.740 --> 00:41:19.789
everyone interprets is a veiled bribe. Now,
this is an example of an indirect speech act,

00:41:19.789 --> 00:41:26.049
a case in which you don't blurt out exactly
what you say but you veil it in innuendo expecting

00:41:26.049 --> 00:41:32.529
your listener to listen between the lines.
Another example, "If you could pass the guacamole,

00:41:32.529 --> 00:41:37.260
that would be awesome." This is a polite request
when you think about it, it doesn't make a

00:41:37.260 --> 00:41:46.550
whole lot of sense. But nonetheless, it is
instantly understood as a request. "We're

00:41:46.550 --> 00:41:51.650
counting on you to show leadership in our
Campaign for the Future." Anyone who's been

00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:57.369
unfortunate enough to sit through a fund raising
dinner is familiar with euphemistic snoring

00:41:57.369 --> 00:42:05.079
like that that is a solicitation for a donation.
"Would you like to come up and see my etchings?"

00:42:05.079 --> 00:42:10.170
This has been recognized as a sexual come
on for so long that in 1932, James Thurber

00:42:10.170 --> 00:42:15.260
could draw a cartoon with a confused young
man saying to his date, "You wait here and

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:23.690
I'll bring the etchings down." And then, "Nice
store you got there. It would be a real shame

00:42:23.690 --> 00:42:28.490
if something happened to it," is something
that we all recognize as veiled threat. So

00:42:28.490 --> 00:42:34.559
the puzzle is why are bribes, request, seductions,
solicitations, and threats so often veiled,

00:42:34.559 --> 00:42:40.730
when both parties know exactly what they mean?
This isn't just an academic puzzle but it

00:42:40.730 --> 00:42:45.000
has a great deal of practical importance such
as in the crafting and interpretation of a

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:50.500
language of treaties and diplomacy, and in
the prosecution of extortion, bribery, and

00:42:50.500 --> 00:42:57.089
sexual harassment which are often conveyed
by innuendo rather than overtly. The solution

00:42:57.089 --> 00:43:04.020
turns out to be more complicated than I thought
when I tried to explain the phenomenon, and

00:43:04.020 --> 00:43:09.430
I think there are at least three components
to the solution. The logic of plausible deniability,

00:43:09.430 --> 00:43:14.950
the logic of relationship negotiation, and
the logic of mutual knowledge, and I'll explain

00:43:14.950 --> 00:43:20.500
what I mean by each of those. Let me start
with the--with, what the game theorist and

00:43:20.500 --> 00:43:25.100
noble prize winner, Thomas Schelling called
the identification problem. Now, how do you

00:43:25.100 --> 00:43:30.040
deal with another intelligent agent when you
don't know his or her values? Bribing a police

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:35.059
officer being a prime example. Imagine that
you had two choices, when you're pulled over,

00:43:35.059 --> 00:43:43.490
either to utter a blatant naked bribe or not
to bribe the officer. What will happen? Well,

00:43:43.490 --> 00:43:49.289
it depends very much on what kind of officer
you get. You could get a dishonest officer

00:43:49.289 --> 00:43:56.420
who might--would accept the bribe, giving
you the very high payoff of going free or

00:43:56.420 --> 00:44:00.910
you might have an honest officer who not only
would rebuff the bribe but might arrest you

00:44:00.910 --> 00:44:05.240
for attempting to bribe an officer in which
you'd have a very high cost of an arrest for

00:44:05.240 --> 00:44:12.860
bribery. So, neither option in this row is--I'm
sorry--neither row is appealing. Both of them

00:44:12.860 --> 00:44:18.069
involve a significant cost. But given this
situation, you're better off with a traffic

00:44:18.069 --> 00:44:23.140
ticket than risking the arrest for bribery.
But now imagine you had a third option, namely

00:44:23.140 --> 00:44:28.950
to issue a veiled bribe through innuendo,
like I was wondering if maybe we could take

00:44:28.950 --> 00:44:34.391
care of it here. Well, if you have a dishonest
officer, he could sniff out the bribe in the

00:44:34.391 --> 00:44:40.440
innuendo and you get a very high payoff of
going free from an overt bribe. If you have

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:45.079
an honest officer, even if he suspected the
bribe he couldn't make it stick in court because

00:44:45.079 --> 00:44:49.210
of the demand of proving something beyond
a reasonable doubt, and so the worst you would

00:44:49.210 --> 00:44:54.390
get is a traffic ticket. So you get the high
payoff of an overt bribe with a relatively

00:44:54.390 --> 00:45:00.369
small cost of not bribing at all, all combined
in one option so the veiled bribe is the rational

00:45:00.369 --> 00:45:10.260
choice. This is the logic of plausible deniability.
But the reason it's not enough is that what

00:45:10.260 --> 00:45:19.119
about non-legal contexts? It's not as if we
spend our lives in legal jeopardy of a particular

00:45:19.119 --> 00:45:24.140
pre-defined legal penalties or proving something
in a court of law. What about when you want

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:28.940
to bribe someone in everyday life. Now you
might say, "Well, why a law-abiding citizen

00:45:28.940 --> 00:45:34.580
want to offer a bribe in everyday life?" Well,
how about this? You want to go to the hottest

00:45:34.580 --> 00:45:39.950
restaurant in town. You have no reservation.
Why not slip the maitre d' a $20 bill and

00:45:39.950 --> 00:45:45.359
see if you can be seated immediately in exchange
for the 20? Well, this was the assignment

00:45:45.359 --> 00:45:50.809
given to the food writer, Bruce Feiler by
Gourmet Magazine on a dare from the editor,

00:45:50.809 --> 00:45:55.130
and he had to write up his experiences in
doing that. And I found that write-up, as

00:45:55.130 --> 00:46:01.200
a psychologist, utterly fascinating. First
of all, it was marked by extreme anxiety.

00:46:01.200 --> 00:46:08.490
As far as I know, no one has ever been sent
to jail for attempting to bribe a maitre d'.

00:46:08.490 --> 00:46:13.440
Nonetheless, he begins his article as follows:
"I am nervous. Truly nervous. As the taxi

00:46:13.440 --> 00:46:17.599
bounces through the trendier neighborhoods
of Manhattan, I keep imagining the possible

00:46:17.599 --> 00:46:23.260
retorts of some incensed maitre d': What kind
of establishment do you think this is? How

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:30.990
dare you insult me? Do you think you can get
in with that?" Second, when you did screw

00:46:30.990 --> 00:46:37.619
up the courage to offer a bribe, he instinctively
veiled it in an innuendo. He would say things

00:46:37.619 --> 00:46:43.809
like: "I hope you can fit us in." Or, "Can
you speed up my wait?" Or, "I was wondering

00:46:43.809 --> 00:46:50.260
if you might have a cancellation." Or, "This
is really important night for me." The third

00:46:50.260 --> 00:46:56.049
interesting finding was the outcome, which
is that he was invariably seated in between

00:46:56.049 --> 00:47:00.690
two and four minutes to the astonishment of
his girlfriend. This is something that's worth

00:47:00.690 --> 00:47:05.640
knowing next time you want to gets in a chic
San Francisco restaurant on a Saturday night

00:47:05.640 --> 00:47:11.650
with no reservations. So what's going on here?
Well, here's a general theory that language

00:47:11.650 --> 00:47:17.690
has to do two things. You have to convey the
particular content like a bribe, a command,

00:47:17.690 --> 00:47:22.140
or a proposition. At the same time, you have
to negotiate the kind of relationship you

00:47:22.140 --> 00:47:27.029
have with the person. The solution is to use
language at these two levels. The literal

00:47:27.029 --> 00:47:32.569
form is consistent with the safest relationship
you have with the listener. The speaker then

00:47:32.569 --> 00:47:37.549
counts on the listener reading between the
lines to entertain a proposition that may

00:47:37.549 --> 00:47:43.859
be incompatible with that relationship. And
politeness is a straightforward case. What's

00:47:43.859 --> 00:47:48.279
going on with "If you could pass the guacamole,
that would be awesome." For one thing, you

00:47:48.279 --> 00:47:56.750
have to admit it's kind of an overstatement.
It would literally be inspiring awe. Also,

00:47:56.750 --> 00:48:01.589
why are you pondering a hypothetical possible
worlds right there and then at the dinner

00:48:01.589 --> 00:48:10.040
table? Well, the listener, amusing that the
speaker is not mad, figures that the speaker

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:14.420
says an outcome is good; therefore, he must
be requesting it. The overall effect is that

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:20.060
the intended content mainly the imperative
gets through. But crucially without the presumption

00:48:20.060 --> 00:48:24.829
of dominance, that is, without the impression
that you are treating your listener as some

00:48:24.829 --> 00:48:30.860
kind of underling or flunky. So if dominance
is one of the relations that people try to

00:48:30.860 --> 00:48:35.269
avoid in their speech, what are the other
relationships that people are sensitive to?

00:48:35.269 --> 00:48:39.980
Well, an anthropologist named Alan Fiske has
argued that dominance is one of three major

00:48:39.980 --> 00:48:46.500
types of human relationships that characterize
social interaction in all of the world's cultures.

00:48:46.500 --> 00:48:51.539
Each prescribes a distinct way of distributing
resources. Each has a distinct evolutionary

00:48:51.539 --> 00:48:57.760
basis. And each applies most naturally to
certain people but can be extended via language

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:05.470
to others. So, there's dominance whose ethos
is "don't mess with me," and which must have

00:49:05.470 --> 00:49:11.510
come from the dominance hierarchies that are
ubiquitous among the primates. There's a very

00:49:11.510 --> 00:49:17.609
different mindset of communality where the
ethos is "share and share alike," which is

00:49:17.609 --> 00:49:22.789
probably the product of kin selection and
mutualism, and is naturally applied to kin,

00:49:22.789 --> 00:49:27.880
spouses, and close friends. And then there's
reciprocity. The ethos of "if you scratch

00:49:27.880 --> 00:49:35.450
my back and I'll scratch yours," the tit for
tat trading of goods and services in a business-like

00:49:35.450 --> 00:49:42.900
manner that follows the loss of reciprocal
altruism. Now, critically, people distinguish

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:46.970
these kinds of relationships. And a behavior
that's acceptable in one relationship type

00:49:46.970 --> 00:49:53.369
can be anomalous in another. So at a cocktail
party, you might go over to your girlfriend's

00:49:53.369 --> 00:49:57.250
plate and help yourself to a shrimp off her
plate. But you wouldn't go up to your boss

00:49:57.250 --> 00:50:03.520
and help yourself to a shrimp off his plate,
because that would be confusing the communality

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:10.640
relationship that couples have with the dominance
relationship that a supervisor commands. Or

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:14.279
at the end of a dinner party, if you were
to pull out your wallet and offer to pay your

00:50:14.279 --> 00:50:18.920
host for the cost of the food, that would
not be perceived as polite. That would be

00:50:18.920 --> 00:50:23.779
perceived as rude. And the reason is that
it applies the reciprocity mindset that would

00:50:23.779 --> 00:50:30.950
be appropriate on a store to a communal friendly
gathering where the ethos is communality.

00:50:30.950 --> 00:50:35.900
Now, when in those situations where relationships
are ambiguous, divergent understanding can

00:50:35.900 --> 00:50:41.809
be costly. That is, we experience an unpleasant
emotion. We have a name for it: awkwardness,

00:50:41.809 --> 00:50:47.049
when the two parties aren't sure of the relationship
type. For example, there could be moments

00:50:47.049 --> 00:50:51.450
of awkwardness in the work place where an
employee doesn't know whether he can refer

00:50:51.450 --> 00:50:57.970
to his boss on a first name basis or invite
him after work for a beer. It's well-known

00:50:57.970 --> 00:51:03.589
that good friends should not engage in a business
transaction like one selling his car to the

00:51:03.589 --> 00:51:08.590
other, that it put a strain on the friendship,
because these are reciprocity and communality

00:51:08.590 --> 00:51:14.839
are diametrically opposed ways of dealing
with resources. The conflict between dominance

00:51:14.839 --> 00:51:23.119
and sex is when a supervisor solicits an employee,
defines the battleground for sexual harassment.

00:51:23.119 --> 00:51:29.779
And the conflict between friendship and sex
is what makes dating such a fraught domain

00:51:29.779 --> 00:51:36.609
in the subject of so many situation comedies.
Well, this gives rise to a social identification

00:51:36.609 --> 00:51:41.800
problem where the social costs of awkwardness
from mismatched relationship type can duplicate

00:51:41.800 --> 00:51:48.119
the payoff matrix of the legal identification
problem that is raised by bribing a cop. And

00:51:48.119 --> 00:51:52.430
bribing a maitre d' is a perfect example where
the clash is between the authorities that

00:51:52.430 --> 00:51:59.160
a maitre d' ordinarily exerts over its fiefdom
and the reciprocity that you are raising by

00:51:59.160 --> 00:52:05.770
the possibility of the bribe. So, once again,
your choices are: offer a bribe. If your choice

00:52:05.770 --> 00:52:09.870
is would just offer a bribe or don't offer
a bribe, the results would depend on whether

00:52:09.870 --> 00:52:14.250
you got a corrupt maitre d' who would accept
it and seat you immediately, or a scrupulous

00:52:14.250 --> 00:52:19.049
maitre d' who would say, "How dare you insult
me. What kind of establishment do you think

00:52:19.049 --> 00:52:25.690
that is?" If you don't offer a bribe, you
accept the dominance relationship of the maitre

00:52:25.690 --> 00:52:30.410
d' and you avoid the awkwardness but you'll
just have the long wait for the table. If

00:52:30.410 --> 00:52:34.869
you offer the bribe, then if you have a corrupt
maitre d' who consummates the reciprocity

00:52:34.869 --> 00:52:39.329
relationship, you get the quick table. When
you have the scrupulous ones who continue

00:52:39.329 --> 00:52:44.910
to maintain dominance when you're suggesting
reciprocity, you get that unpleasant emotion

00:52:44.910 --> 00:52:52.420
called "awkwardness." If you say, "I was hoping
there might be a cancellation," on the other

00:52:52.420 --> 00:52:56.710
hand, the corrupt maitre d' could sense the
bribe and you get the high benefit of the

00:52:56.710 --> 00:53:01.000
quick table. The scrupulous one could choice
to ignore it, and the worst that you'd have

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:07.970
is the long wait preserving the harmony of
relationship type. So this is--I think there's

00:53:07.970 --> 00:53:13.740
one problem that still remains, even solving
the maitre d' problem, which is that people

00:53:13.740 --> 00:53:18.950
aren't naïve. How do you deal with the problem
of meta-knowledge the fact that usually both

00:53:18.950 --> 00:53:25.090
parties know when an overture has been made
by innuendo? Life isn't a court of law. You

00:53:25.090 --> 00:53:31.549
don't have to prove it beyond a reasonable
doubt. And so, any deniability is not in fact

00:53:31.549 --> 00:53:38.329
all that plausible at all. Why should an obvious
indirect overture feel less awkward than an

00:53:38.329 --> 00:53:44.549
overture that is in so many words and that--and
hence is on the record. Now, illustrate that

00:53:44.549 --> 00:53:50.340
with a scene from the romantic comedy "When
Harry Met Sally." Early on the film when the

00:53:50.340 --> 00:53:55.490
couple has just met, Harry makes a sexual
comment and Sally says, "You're coming on

00:53:55.490 --> 00:53:59.829
to me." And he says, "What do you want me
to about it? I take it back. Okay? I take

00:53:59.829 --> 00:54:04.500
it back." And she says, "You can't take it
back." And he says, "Why not?" She says, "Because

00:54:04.500 --> 00:54:09.359
it's already out there." He says, "Oh, jeez.
What are we supposed to do? Call the cops?

00:54:09.359 --> 00:54:14.160
It's already out there." So the puzzle is
what is the status of an overture that is

00:54:14.160 --> 00:54:20.000
sensed to be "out there" or "on the record"
or "once said, can't be unsaid," that makes

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:25.260
it so much worse than a veiled overture that's
implicated indirectly? Well, there are a number

00:54:25.260 --> 00:54:30.650
of answers, but I think the most compelling
is the concept that logicians and economist

00:54:30.650 --> 00:54:36.510
sometimes call "mutual knowledge or common
knowledge" which must be differentiated from

00:54:36.510 --> 00:54:42.850
identical individual knowledge. In the individual
knowledge: A knows X and B know X. In mutual

00:54:42.850 --> 00:54:48.890
knowledge: A knows X, B knows X, A knows that
B knows X, B knows that A knows X, A knows

00:54:48.890 --> 00:54:57.529
that B knows that A knows X add in as an item.
Now, this is a distinction with a difference

00:54:57.529 --> 00:55:04.839
that there are qualitative differences between
shared identical knowledge and mutual or common

00:55:04.839 --> 00:55:10.519
knowledge in a technical sense. And a couple
of everyday examples are: 1) why do democracy

00:55:10.519 --> 00:55:17.210
enshrine freedom of assembly as a fundamental
right and why are so many political revolutions

00:55:17.210 --> 00:55:22.579
instigated when a crowd assembles in a public
square. Well, before the assembly, everyone

00:55:22.579 --> 00:55:27.539
may have known that they were disgruntled,
but when everyone comes together for that

00:55:27.539 --> 00:55:33.859
reason, now everyone knows that everyone else
knows that everyone is disgruntled. That mutual

00:55:33.859 --> 00:55:38.569
knowledge can embolden people to challenge
the authority relationship and bring down

00:55:38.569 --> 00:55:44.099
a dictator who would otherwise be able to
pick people off one at the time. Likewise,

00:55:44.099 --> 00:55:49.670
the whole point of the Emperor's New Clothes
story depends on the concept of mutual knowledge.

00:55:49.670 --> 00:55:53.960
With the little voice said the Emperor is
naked. He wasn't telling anyone anything they

00:55:53.960 --> 00:55:59.750
didn't already know, individually. But, he
was conveying information nonetheless. Now,

00:55:59.750 --> 00:56:04.349
everyone knew that everyone else knew and
that everyone else knew that they knew, once

00:56:04.349 --> 00:56:08.450
again that could change the relationship and
they could challenge the authority of the

00:56:08.450 --> 00:56:14.339
Emperor. The moral of this is that language
is a very good way of exploding individual

00:56:14.339 --> 00:56:20.539
knowledge into mutual knowledge. The hypothesis
is that innuendoes merely provide individual

00:56:20.539 --> 00:56:25.640
knowledge where as direct speech provides
mutual knowledge and it's mutual knowledge

00:56:25.640 --> 00:56:31.700
that is a trigger for maintaining or changing
a relationship. So, if Harry were to say,

00:56:31.700 --> 00:56:36.410
"Would you like to come up and see my etchings,"
Sally knows that she has turned down an overture.

00:56:36.410 --> 00:56:41.549
Harry knows that she has turned down an overture.
But does Sally know that Harry knows? She

00:56:41.549 --> 00:56:46.250
could think to herself, "Maybe Harry thinks
I'm naive." And does Harry know that Sally

00:56:46.250 --> 00:56:52.490
knows that he knows? Harry might wonder, "Maybe
Sally thinks I'm dense." There is no mutual

00:56:52.490 --> 00:56:56.910
knowledge and they can maintain the fiction
of a friendship. Whereas if Harry where to

00:56:56.910 --> 00:57:01.360
have said, "Would you like to come up and
have sex?" Then, Harry knows that Sally knows

00:57:01.360 --> 00:57:05.940
that Harry knows that Sally knows, they cannot
maintain the fiction of a friendship. And

00:57:05.940 --> 00:57:10.750
I think this is what's behind the intuition
that with overt speech, you can't take it

00:57:10.750 --> 00:57:16.280
back, it's out there. To sum up language as
a window into social relationships, people

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:21.299
have to convey messages while unsure of their
relationship, indirect speech could minimize

00:57:21.299 --> 00:57:26.960
the risks in legal context with tangible costs
like bribes and threats. The same thing could

00:57:26.960 --> 00:57:32.450
happen in everyday life because relationship
mismatches could have an emotional cost. And

00:57:32.450 --> 00:57:37.390
finally, indirect speech prevents individual
knowledge from becoming mutual knowledge and

00:57:37.390 --> 00:57:42.410
its mutual knowledge that's the basis for
a relationship. Okay, we'll now I'm going

00:57:42.410 --> 00:57:52.500
to begin the end of my talk. In a psychology,
one often faces the problem of overcoming

00:57:52.500 --> 00:58:00.180
people's familiarity with their own mental
processes and way of life to nullify the anesthetic

00:58:00.180 --> 00:58:05.820
of familiarity, to make a familiar seem strange.
And one way of doing that is by framing the

00:58:05.820 --> 00:58:13.279
problem, in terms of being a Martian scientist.
How would a Martian biologist arriving on

00:58:13.279 --> 00:58:19.140
earth with no preconceptions characterize
our species? Today's question is how would

00:58:19.140 --> 00:58:25.690
a Martian linguist describe our species documenting
our nature just from the way we use language?

00:58:25.690 --> 00:58:31.180
Well, I think you could say a lot when it
comes to human cognition, the Martian linguist

00:58:31.180 --> 00:58:35.809
would say that humans have an intuitive theory
of the physical world. They locate things

00:58:35.809 --> 00:58:41.529
in space by identifying places and locating
objects in qualitative relationships to them.

00:58:41.529 --> 00:58:46.910
They construe matter as formless stuff or
discrete things which are stretched along

00:58:46.910 --> 00:58:51.869
one, two or three dimensions. They order and
package events in time, relative to their

00:58:51.869 --> 00:58:57.609
own motion, moment of consciousness, and they
explain events by identifying their causes

00:58:57.609 --> 00:59:03.940
namely an actor that impinges on an entity.
Human intuitive physics differs from real

00:59:03.940 --> 00:59:09.039
physics, but it helps them to reason and agree
about aspects of reality relevant to their

00:59:09.039 --> 00:59:15.109
purposes, their understanding of cause and
effect, what they can know, change and will,

00:59:15.109 --> 00:59:22.059
how they package and quantify their experience
and how they assign moral responsibility.

00:59:22.059 --> 00:59:28.400
People not only have ideas, but they steep
them with emotion. They stand in awe of deities.

00:59:28.400 --> 00:59:35.740
They are terrified by disease, death and infirmity.
They are revolted by bodily secretions. They

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:41.950
loathe enemies, traitors and subordinate peoples.
They take a prurient interest in sexuality

00:59:41.950 --> 00:59:47.720
in all its variations. Despite having negative
reactions to so many thoughts, humans willingly

00:59:47.720 --> 00:59:52.240
inflict these thoughts on one another; to
remind them of the unpleasant nature of certain

00:59:52.240 --> 00:59:57.780
things, to intimidate or denigrate them, to
get their attention, or to advertise their

00:59:57.780 --> 01:00:04.220
reactions to life's frustrations and setbacks.
When it comes to human social life, humans

01:00:04.220 --> 01:00:10.450
are very, very touchy about their relationships.
With some of their fellows typically kin,

01:00:10.450 --> 01:00:16.740
lovers and friends, humans freely share and
do favors. With others, they jockey for dominance.

01:00:16.740 --> 01:00:22.640
With still others, they trade goods and services
on a tit-for-tat basis. People distinguish

01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:27.240
these relationships sharply. When one person
breaches the logic of a relationship with

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:32.829
another, they both suffer an emotional cost.
Nonetheless humans often risk these breaches,

01:00:32.829 --> 01:00:38.720
sometimes to get on with the business of life,
sometimes to renegotiate their relationship.

01:00:38.720 --> 01:00:43.980
Finally, humans think a lot about what other
humans thinks about them, and their relationship

01:00:43.980 --> 01:00:49.180
are ratified by this mutual knowledge. They
know that others know they know what kind

01:00:49.180 --> 01:00:54.470
of relationship they share. As a result, to
perverse their relationships while transacting

01:00:54.470 --> 01:00:59.869
the business of their lives, humans often
engage in hypocrisy and taboo. And those are

01:00:59.869 --> 01:01:04.470
some of the ways in which language can serve
as a window into human nature. Thank you very

